{{mergeto|Casuistry|discuss=Talk:Casuistry#Jesuitism merger proposal|date=August 2017}}

'''Jesuitism''' is a [[casuistic]] approach to moral questions and problems, so called because it was promoted by some [[Jesuits]] of the 17th century. The earliest known citation is 1622.{{cn|date=November 2018}}

Some Jesuit theologians,{{who|date=November 2018}} in view of promoting personal responsibility and the respect of [[freedom of conscience]], stressed the importance of the 'case by case' approach to personal moral decisions and ultimately developed and accepted a [[casuistry]] (the study of ''cases of consciences'') where at the time of decision, individual inclinations were more important than the moral law itself.  A British encyclopedia of 1900 claimed that it was "popularly regarded as an attempt to achieve holy ends by unholy means."<ref>[http://www.fromoldbooks.org/Wood-NuttallEncyclopaedia/j/jesuitism.html Nuttall Encyclopædia of General Knowledge]</ref>

[[Blaise Pascal]], the French [[mathematician]], religious philosopher and [[Jansenist]] sympathiser, vigorously attacked the moral [[laxism]] of such Jesuits in his famous ''[[Lettres provinciales]]'' of 1656-57.{{cn|date=November 2018}} It is considered suspect by many moral theologians.{{who|date=November 2018}}

